==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Precede
<hw>Pre*cede"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Preceded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Preceding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>praecedere</ets>,
<ets>praecessum</ets>; <ets>prae</ets> before + <ets>cedere</ets> to go,
to be in motion: cf. F. <ets>pr⟦eacute⟧ceder</ets>. See <er>Pre-</er>,
and <er>Cede</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To go before in order of
time; to occur first with relation to anything.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Harm
<xex>precedes</xex> not sin.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To go before in place, rank, or
importance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to be preceded; to preface; to introduce;
-- used with <xex>by</xex> or <xex>with</xex> before the instrumental
object.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is usual to <qex>precede</qex> hostilities by a public
declaration.</q> <rj><qau>Kent.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Precedency</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Precedence</ent>⟦br⟧
